Variable selection (exclude variables with only one value or duplicate) and change names of variables

# variable selection
IDB_sub <- IDB |>
  select(-DT_GERACAO, -HH_GERACAO, -ANO_ELEICAO, -SG_UF, -CD_MUN_SIT_BIOMETRICA, -DS_MUN_SIT_BIOMETRICA, -NR_ZONA, -CD_GENERO, -DS_ESTADO_CIVIL, -DS_FAIXA_ETARIA, -DS_GRAU_ESCOLARIDADE)

# change names from Portuguese to English
IDB_sub <- IDB_sub |>
  rename(
    cd_muni = CD_MUNICIPIO,
    name_muni = NM_MUNICIPIO,
    num_sec = NR_SECAO,
    num_stat = NR_LOCAL_VOTACAO,
    sex = DS_GENERO,
    cd_marit = CD_ESTADO_CIVIL,
    cd_age = CD_FAIXA_ETARIA,
    cd_edu = CD_GRAU_ESCOLARIDADE,
    elig_vote = QT_ELEITORES_PERFIL,
    elig_bio = QT_ELEITORES_BIOMETRIA,
    elig_dis = QT_ELEITORES_DEFICIENCIA,
    elig_req = QT_ELEITORES_INC_NM_SOCIAL
  )

# correct class of variables
IDB_sub <- IDB_sub |>
  mutate(cd_muni = as.factor(cd_muni),
         name_muni = as.factor(name_muni),
         sex = as.factor(sex),
         cd_marit = as.factor(cd_marit),
         cd_age = as.factor(cd_age),
         cd_edu = as.factor(cd_edu),
         )

# create another educational category

IDB_sub <- IDB_sub |>
  filter(!cd_edu == "0") |>   # remove samples without information regarding education
  mutate(educ_cat = if_else(cd_edu == 8, "Higher", if_else(cd_edu %in% c(7,6) , "Highshool", "Other")))

# create another age category
IDB_sub <- IDB_sub |>
  filter(!cd_age == "-3") |> # remove samples without information regarding age
  mutate(age_cat = if_else(cd_age %in% c(1600, 1700, 1800, 1900), "Under20", if_else(cd_age %in% c(6064, 6569, 7074, 7579, 8084, 8589, 9094, 9599, 9999) , "Over60", "Other")))


# change values from Portugees to English
IDB_sub$sex <- recode(IDB_sub$sex, "FEMININO" = "female", "MASCULINO"= "male")

IDB_sub$cd_marit <- recode(IDB_sub$cd_marit, "1" = "Single", "3" = "Married", "5" = "Widowed", "7" = "Legally Separated", "9" = "Divorced")

Pick up top 10 cities with large participants # change categorical values (name_muni).. Next Step

top10_cities <- IDB_sub |> 
  group_by(name_muni) |>
  summarise(count = n(), .groups = "drop_last") |>
  arrange(desc(count))　|>
  head(10)

IDB_top10 <- IDB_sub |>
  filter(name_muni %in% top10_cities$name_muni)

IDB_top10$name_muni <- recode(IDB_top10$name_muni, "LISBOA" = "Lisbon", "NOVA YORK" = "New York", "MIL\xc3O" = "Milan", "NAG\xd3IA" = "Nagoya", "MADRI" = "Madrid", "MIAMI" = "Miami", 
"LONDRES" = "London", "T\xd3QUIO" = "Tokyo", "BOSTON" = "Boston", "PORTO" = "Porto") 

IDB_top10 |>
  group_by(name_muni) |>
  summarise(Total = n()) |>
  arrange(desc(Total))

Create graph

# by cities by sex
IDB_top10 |>
  group_by(name_muni, sex) |>
  summarise(Total = n(), .groups = "drop") |>
  ggplot(aes(x = reorder(name_muni, -Total), y = Total, fill = sex)) +
  geom_col() +
  labs(x = "Top-10 Cities", y = "Total") +
  scale_y_continuous(breaks = seq(0, max(20000), by = 2000)) +
  theme_minimal()

# by cities by marital status
IDB_top10 |>
  group_by(name_muni, cd_marit) |>
  summarise(Total = n(), .groups = "drop") |>
  ggplot(aes(x = reorder(name_muni, -Total), y = Total, fill = cd_marit)) +
  geom_col() +
  labs(x = "Top-10 Cities", y = "Total") +
  scale_y_continuous(breaks = seq(0, max(20000), by = 2000)) +
  theme_minimal()

# by cities by educational categories
IDB_top10 |>
  group_by(name_muni, educ_cat) |>
  summarise(Total = n(), .groups = "drop") |>
  ggplot(aes(x = reorder(name_muni, -Total), y = Total, fill = educ_cat)) +
  geom_col() +
  labs(x = "Top-10 Cities", y = "Total") +
  scale_y_continuous(breaks = seq(0, max(20000), by = 2000)) +
  theme_minimal()
